Owner: Operations Lead
Approved By: CEO
Effective Date: March 2026

1. Purpose
This Business Continuity Plan describes how Kahana will continue critical operations and services—especially Kahana Oasis—during and after a disruption (e.g., infrastructure outages, office inaccessibility, major incidents). The goal is to minimize downtime for customers and maintain essential internal functions.

This plan supports SOC 2 Security and Availability criteria by defining continuity objectives, response roles, and recovery coordination requirements.

2. Scope
This BCP covers:

Kahana Oasis production service (web app, APIs, data storage).

Supporting infrastructure and platforms (cloud provider, identity/SSO, monitoring, CI/CD as needed to support continuity).

Critical business functions:

Service availability and customer access to workspaces and content.

Customer support and communication.

Key internal operations (engineering, security, billing as needed).

It applies to disruptions such as: cloud or network outages, loss of office access (e.g., Chandigarh), major supplier failure, regional incidents, and serious internal system failures.

3. Business Impact and Critical Functions
Kahana identifies the following as critical:

Kahana Oasis availability: Customers must be able to log in and access their hubs and content.

Customer support and incident communication: Ability to respond to customer issues and provide timely updates.

Data integrity and access: Preservation and access to customer data and core configuration.

Target objectives:

Recovery Time Objective (RTO):

Kahana Oasis core service: 4–8 hours.

Customer support channels (email/helpdesk): 4 hours.

Recovery Point Objective (RPO):

Customer production data: 24 hours maximum acceptable data loss (Supabase Pro daily backups); N/A if on Free Plan (no backups).

4. Assumptions
This plan assumes:

AWS (us-east-1) and Supabase remain generally available outside specific regional or service issues.

Critical team members can work remotely if office is unavailable.

Backups and monitoring are functioning as defined in Backup/DR and Logging policies.

5. Continuity Strategies by Scenario
5.1 Cloud / Infrastructure Outage (Partial or Regional)
Use multi‑AZ or multi‑zone architecture where possible for critical components.

Current state note: Kahana operates AWS + Supabase without a secondary live database. For regional failures, DR focuses on restoring service from backups and infrastructure-as-code rather than immediate active failover.

Priorities:

Restore core APIs and web front‑end.

Restore database and storage access.

Restore non‑critical background jobs and analytics.

RTO/RPO execution target for this scenario:
- RTO: 4-8 hours for core Oasis service
- RPO: up to 24 hours data loss when relying on Supabase Pro daily backups

5.2 Kahana Office Unavailable (e.g., Chandigarh)
All critical roles can work remotely using laptops and secure remote access.

Office‑bound functions (e.g., physical paperwork) are deferred or moved to digital processes where possible.

Communication continues via remote collaboration tools (chat, video, email); leadership confirms expectations with the team.

5.3 Major Application Incident (Functional Degradation)
Activate Incident Response Plan for technical triage and containment.

Prioritize restoration of “read” access to customer content, then full functionality.

Use feature flags or temporary disablement of non‑critical features to stabilize the platform.

5.4 Key Vendor or Third‑Party Failure
Identify critical vendors (cloud provider, auth provider, monitoring, critical SaaS).

For each, define:

Available backups or alternatives (secondary provider, manual workaround).

How to quickly switch if provider is down or compromised.

Communicate clearly to customers if a third‑party outage is affecting service.

6. Roles and Responsibilities in a BCP Event
BCP Coordinator (often Operations Lead or CEO):

Decides when to activate the BCP.

Coordinates efforts across teams.

Technical Lead (Engineering/DevOps):

Executes technical recovery steps (failover, restores, configuration changes).

Customer Support / Success Lead:

Manages customer‑facing communications and expectations.

Communications Lead:

Coordinates internal announcements and status updates (may be same as above in a small team).

HR / Admin:

Supports people‑related logistics (remote work guidance, office access issues).

7. Plan Activation and Escalation
The BCP may be activated when:

Kahana Oasis is or is expected to be unavailable or severely degraded beyond normal incident SLAs.

The primary office is unavailable for an extended period.

A critical vendor outage significantly affects service delivery.

Steps:

BCP Coordinator declares a BCP event and notifies leadership and key staff.

An incident/BCP channel is created (e.g., dedicated chat room) and a record opened.

Roles for this event (Coordinator, Technical Lead, Communications Lead) are assigned if not predefined.

8. Communication Plan
Internal Communication

Use agreed internal channels (chat, email, calls) for real‑time updates.

Provide concise, regular updates: current status, actions taken, next steps.

Customer Communication

Use appropriate channels (status page, email, in‑app banners) to:

Inform customers of the disruption at a high level.

Provide expected timelines and workarounds (if any).

Share updates at reasonable intervals until resolution.

External / Stakeholder Communication

For significant events, leadership may provide summaries to partners, investors, or others as needed.

9. Data Backup and Recovery Alignment
This BCP works together with the Backup and Disaster Recovery Plan:

Production databases and critical storage are backed up on a defined schedule.

Periodic restore tests verify that backups are usable.

In a continuity event, the Technical Lead follows documented DR steps to restore data and services while meeting RTO/RPO targets as closely as possible.

10. Remote Work and Alternate Work Arrangements
All critical staff must be able to work remotely in case of office disruptions.

Remote access must comply with the Remote Access and Workstation Security policies.

Leadership ensures:

Clear expectations on working hours and availability during a continuity event.

Support for employees affected by local conditions (flexible arrangements where needed).

11. Testing and Exercises
Kahana will test key elements of this BCP at least annually, such as:

Simulated cloud outage and failover or restore scenario.

Office‑unavailability drill (e.g., “work from home day” test).

Each test should have:

Clear objectives.

Documented results and gaps.

Follow‑up actions to improve the plan.

12. Plan Maintenance
The BCP must be reviewed at least annually, and after major changes to:

System architecture or cloud infrastructure.

Office locations or working model.

Critical vendors or service dependencies.

Updates must be approved by the BCP Owner and communicated to affected staff.

13. Relationship to Other Documents
This BCP is supported by, and should be read alongside:

Disaster Recovery Plan (technical recovery procedures).

Incident Response Plan (security/technical incident handling).

Backup and Restoration Policy.

Vendor Management Policy.

Remote Access and Workstation Security policies.